1. Project Overview
EnVault is a self-hosted, zero-knowledge environment variable manager built as a Next.js application deployable to Vercel with a PostgreSQL backend. It solves the problem of securely storing, organizing, and sharing .env secrets across projects, machines, and team members — without trusting any server with plaintext values.
The golden rule: the server stores only ciphertext. Decryption happens exclusively in the browser. Even a full database breach reveals nothing without the user's master password.
Core Problems It Solves
	•	Env vars get lost when switching machines or reinstalling OS
	•	Sharing secrets with team members currently means plaintext Slack/email/WhatsApp
	•	No way to version or organize env vars by project and environment
	•	.gitignore files, API keys, private instructions — all need a secure home
	•	Accessing secrets from a new device requires complete manual re-entry
What Makes It Different
	•	Zero-knowledge architecture — no master password ever leaves the device, not even hashed
	•	Folder-within-folder organization — mirrors real project structures (ai/, frontend/, backend/)
	•	Two-layer access — account login + vault master password required before any secret is visible
	•	Secure share links — time-limited, one-time tokens with recipient-side decryption
	•	Generic file vault — store any text file: instructions, notes, keys, anything in .gitignore
	•	100% Next.js — no separate backend, no microservices, one Vercel deployment

2. Security Architecture
2.1 Zero-Knowledge Model
EnVault follows a strict zero-knowledge design pattern. The server (Next.js API routes + PostgreSQL) never has access to plaintext secret values at any point. The only data the server stores about secrets is their AES-256-GCM ciphertext, IV, salt, and metadata (key name, project association, timestamps).
What the server sees vs what it never sees
SEES: encrypted blob (ciphertext), IV, salt, key names (metadata only), timestamps, share tokens
NEVER SEES: plaintext values, master password, derived encryption key, decrypted content
NEVER SEES: share passphrase, recipient's decryption key, any data in transit after TLS
2.2 Encryption Model
Master Password → Encryption Key (PBKDF2)
The user's master password is never stored. Instead it is used as input to PBKDF2 (Password-Based Key Derivation Function 2) to derive a 256-bit AES key in the browser using the Web Crypto API. This process uses:
	•	Algorithm: PBKDF2 with SHA-256
	•	Iterations: 600,000 rounds (OWASP 2024 recommendation)
	•	Salt: 32 bytes of cryptographically secure random data (stored per-vault in DB)
	•	Output: 256-bit key used directly for AES-256-GCM operations
Encryption: AES-256-GCM
Each secret value is encrypted individually using AES-256-GCM. GCM (Galois/Counter Mode) provides both confidentiality and authentication — meaning any tampering with the ciphertext is detected and decryption fails. Each encryption operation uses:
	•	A fresh, random 12-byte IV (initialization vector) — never reused
	•	The derived key from PBKDF2
	•	AAD (Additional Authenticated Data) set to the key name + project ID for binding
// Browser-side encryption (simplified)
async function encryptValue(plaintext, derivedKey, keyName, projectId) {
  const iv = crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(12));
  const encoded = new TextEncoder().encode(plaintext);
  const aad = new TextEncoder().encode(`${keyName}:${projectId}`);
  const ciphertext = await crypto.subtle.encrypt(
    { name: 'AES-GCM', iv, additionalData: aad, tagLength: 128 },
    derivedKey,
    encoded
  );
  return { ciphertext: toBase64(ciphertext), iv: toBase64(iv) };
}
2.3 Two-Layer Access Control
Getting into the vault requires passing TWO independent security gates:
Layer
Mechanism
Blocks
Managed by
Layer 1
Account auth (NextAuth + JWT)
Anyone without an account
NextAuth session cookie
Layer 2
Vault master password (PBKDF2)
Logged-in users without the master password
Web Crypto API (browser only)
Share gate
Share passphrase + expiry token
Recipients without the passphrase
Time-limited DB token + browser decryption
Layer 2 (vault unlock) is enforced on every page load and after configurable inactivity timeout (default 15 minutes). When a session expires or the user navigates away, the derived key is cleared from memory. The master password must be re-entered to re-derive the key.
2.4 Share Security Model
When sharing a vault folder or project with someone:
	•	A new random 32-byte share salt is generated in the browser
	•	You enter a share passphrase (which you communicate to the recipient separately — out-of-band)
	•	PBKDF2 derives a new share key from the passphrase + share salt
	•	The selected secrets are re-encrypted with the share key and stored as a share bundle in the DB
	•	A time-limited, cryptographically random access token is generated and emailed as a link
	•	Recipient clicks the link → enters the share passphrase → browser decrypts the bundle locally
Share security properties
The share token in the email grants access to the encrypted blob only
Without the passphrase (communicated separately), the blob is useless
Tokens expire (configurable: 24h, 72h, 7d, or single-use)
After access, single-use tokens are deleted immediately
The server never knows the share passphrase — it only verifies the token
Shares are scoped: you can share a single folder, a project, or specific keys
2.5 Threat Model
Threat
Scenario
Mitigation
Database breach
Attacker dumps entire PostgreSQL DB
Only ciphertext stored — useless without master password
Server compromise
Next.js server is fully compromised
Server never holds decrypted values or keys
Intercepted share email
Attacker intercepts the share link email
Link alone is worthless without the share passphrase
Expired tokens
Old share link reused
Tokens have TTL + single-use option
Brute force master password
Attacker has ciphertext, tries passwords
600k PBKDF2 rounds makes brute force extremely slow
Session hijack
Attacker steals session cookie
Vault stays locked — master password still required
XSS attack
Script injected into vault UI
CSP headers, no eval, HttpOnly cookies, input sanitization
MITM attack
Traffic intercepted in transit
HTTPS enforced via Vercel + HSTS headers

3. Feature Specification
3.1 Authentication
	•	Email/password sign-up with email verification (via NextAuth Credentials + Resend)
	•	Magic link login option (email OTP — no password needed for account)
	•	JWT session tokens, HttpOnly cookies, CSRF protection via NextAuth
	•	Account-level 2FA is optional but recommended (TOTP via authenticator app)
3.2 Vault Unlock
	•	Separate from account login — vault requires master password on every new session
	•	Auto-lock after configurable inactivity timeout (5 min, 15 min, 30 min, never)
	•	Lock button always visible in the navbar to manually clear the derived key from memory
	•	Wrong password attempts are rate-limited client-side (exponential backoff)
	•	Master password change: re-encrypts all existing secrets with the new derived key
3.3 Project Management
	•	Create unlimited projects with name, description, color tag, and emoji icon
	•	Projects are the top-level organizational unit (e.g., learn-bridge-ai, my-api)
	•	Each project can contain environments: development, staging, production, custom
	•	Project-level stats: number of secrets, last modified, environments count
3.4 Folder/File Structure
EnVault supports a full recursive folder hierarchy inside each project + environment. This mirrors a real filesystem:
learn-bridge-ai/
├── production/
│   ├── ai/
│   │   ├── OPENAI_API_KEY
│   │   ├── ANTHROPIC_KEY
│   │   └── notes.txt           ← plain text file
│   ├── frontend/
│   │   ├── NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL
│   │   └── NEXTAUTH_SECRET
│   └── backend/
│       ├── DATABASE_URL
│       ├── JWT_SECRET
│       └── deployment-notes.md ← gitignored instructions
└── development/
    └── ai/
        └── OPENAI_API_KEY      ← different value for dev
	•	Folders can be nested infinitely deep
	•	Each folder can contain: env variables (KEY=VALUE pairs) and text files (arbitrary content)
	•	Text files are first-class — perfect for .gitignore instructions, deployment notes, API docs, etc.
	•	Drag-and-drop to reorganize items within the folder tree (planned Phase 2)
	•	Folder-level operations: rename, move, delete (cascades), share, export
3.5 Secret Management
	•	Add variable: KEY name (plaintext, visible) + VALUE (encrypted, hidden by default)
	•	Values are hidden with •••••• mask — click the eye icon to reveal (decrypts in browser)
	•	Inline editing with auto-save — no separate save button needed
	•	Value history: last 5 versions of each secret are kept (all encrypted), with timestamps
	•	Bulk import: paste a .env file → parsed and encrypted entry-by-entry
	•	Export .env: decrypts all values in browser → downloads a .env file locally
	•	Copy to clipboard: copies decrypted value, clipboard cleared after 30 seconds
	•	Search: search by key name across all projects (values are never searched — encrypted)
	•	Tags/labels: add custom tags to secrets for filtering (e.g., 'database', 'third-party')
3.6 Text File Vault
	•	Store any text content as a named file inside any folder
	•	Encrypted and stored identically to env variables — zero-knowledge model applies
	•	Full-screen editor to read and edit encrypted text files
	•	Use cases: deployment instructions, private API documentation, .gitignore'd README sections, private notes
	•	Download as .txt, .md, or .json
3.7 Secure Sharing
	•	Share any scope: a single key, a folder, a full environment, or an entire project
	•	Generates an encrypted share bundle + time-limited access token
	•	Token delivery: email sent via Resend with the share link
	•	Passphrase delivery: communicated out-of-band by the sharer (Slack, call, etc.)
	•	Expiry options: 1 hour, 24 hours, 7 days, 30 days, single-use, never
	•	Recipient UX: opens link → enters passphrase → sees decrypted values → can copy or download .env
	•	Recipient does NOT need an EnVault account
	•	Share management: view all active shares, revoke any share instantly
	•	Share audit log: who accessed a share, when, from what IP
3.8 Import / Export
	•	Import: paste .env content → parsed, individual keys confirmed, then encrypted
	•	Import from .json (key-value format)
	•	Export: download full project as .env, .json, or a zip of per-folder .env files
	•	Export is always a browser-side operation — decrypted locally, never via server

