7. API Routes
All API routes require authentication via NextAuth session unless marked public. The server only ever receives and returns ciphertext for secret values — it has no decryption capability.
Method
Route
Auth
Description
GET
/api/vault/salt
Session
Returns user's PBKDF2 salt. If no vault yet, generates and saves 32 random bytes.
GET
/api/projects
Session
List all projects for the authenticated user
POST
/api/projects
Session
Create a project. Body: {name, description?, color?, emoji?}
GET
/api/folders?envId=
Session
Get full folder tree for an environment
POST
/api/secrets
Session
Store a new secret. Body: {keyName, valueEncrypted, iv, folderId?, environmentId, tags?}
PATCH
/api/secrets/[id]
Session
Update a secret value. Old value is moved to SecretHistory automatically.
GET
/api/secrets/[id]/history
Session
Returns last 5 encrypted historical values for a secret
POST
/api/share
Session
Create share. Body: {bundleEncrypted, bundleIv, shareSalt, scopeType, scopeId, expiresIn, singleUse, recipientEmail?, note?}
GET
/api/share/[token]
Public
Validate token, log access, return {bundleEncrypted, bundleIv, shareSalt, scopeType} or 404/410
POST
/api/share/revoke
Session
Revoke a share by ID. Sets isRevoked=true immediately.

8. Cryptography Implementation
lib/crypto/vault.ts — Key Derivation
// Derives AES-256 key from master password + salt using PBKDF2
// NEVER called server-side. Browser only.
export async function deriveVaultKey(
  masterPassword: string,
  saltBase64: string,
  iterations = 600_000
): Promise<CryptoKey> {
  const salt = fromBase64(saltBase64);
  const keyMaterial = await crypto.subtle.importKey(
    'raw',
    new TextEncoder().encode(masterPassword),
    'PBKDF2',
    false,
    ['deriveKey']
  );
  return crypto.subtle.deriveKey(
    { name: 'PBKDF2', salt, iterations, hash: 'SHA-256' },
    keyMaterial,
    { name: 'AES-GCM', length: 256 },
    false, // not extractable — key never leaves memory as bytes
    ['encrypt', 'decrypt']
  );
}
lib/crypto/encrypt.ts — Encryption
export async function encryptSecret(
  plaintext: string,
  key: CryptoKey,
  aad?: string // Additional Authenticated Data (key name + project id)
): Promise<{ valueEncrypted: string; iv: string }> {
  const iv = crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(12));
  const encoded = new TextEncoder().encode(plaintext);
  const params: AesGcmParams = {
    name: 'AES-GCM', iv, tagLength: 128,
    ...(aad && { additionalData: new TextEncoder().encode(aad) })
  };
  const ciphertext = await crypto.subtle.encrypt(params, key, encoded);
  return { valueEncrypted: toBase64(ciphertext), iv: toBase64(iv) };
}
lib/store/vaultStore.ts — In-Memory Key Management
// Zustand store — CryptoKey lives here, cleared on lock
interface VaultStore {
  derivedKey: CryptoKey | null;
  isUnlocked: boolean;
  lastActivity: number;
  unlock: (key: CryptoKey) => void;
  lock: () => void;
  touchActivity: () => void;
}
 
export const useVaultStore = create<VaultStore>((set) => ({
  derivedKey: null,
  isUnlocked: false,
  lastActivity: 0,
  unlock: (key) => set({ derivedKey: key, isUnlocked: true, lastActivity: Date.now() }),
  lock: () => set({ derivedKey: null, isUnlocked: false }),
  touchActivity: () => set({ lastActivity: Date.now() }),
}));
 
// Auto-lock watcher (called from vault layout)
export function useAutoLock(timeoutMs = 15 * 60 * 1000) {
  const { lastActivity, lock, isUnlocked } = useVaultStore();
  useEffect(() => {
    if (!isUnlocked) return;
    const interval = setInterval(() => {
      if (Date.now() - lastActivity > timeoutMs) lock();
    }, 30_000); // check every 30 seconds
    return () => clearInterval(interval);
  }, [lastActivity, isUnlocked, lock, timeoutMs]);
}

9. Share & Access System
9.1 Creating a Share (Sharer Flow)
This entire flow happens in the browser before anything is sent to the server:
	•	User selects scope to share (project / environment / folder / specific keys)
	•	User enters a share passphrase in the ShareModal
	•	Browser generates 32 random bytes as shareSalt
	•	PBKDF2 derives shareKey from passphrase + shareSalt (same algorithm, 600k iterations)
	•	Browser fetches the encrypted secrets for the scope, decrypts them with the vault key
	•	Re-encrypts each secret with the shareKey into a share bundle
	•	POST to /api/share with {bundleEncrypted, bundleIv, shareSalt, scopeType, recipientEmail, expiresIn, singleUse}
Server generates a cryptographically random access token (crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('url-safe')), saves the share record, and sends the recipient an email with the link. The passphrase never touches the server.
9.2 Accessing a Share (Recipient Flow)
	•	Recipient receives email with link: https://envault.app/share/[token]
	•	Browser calls GET /api/share/[token] — server validates token, checks expiry, logs access
	•	Server returns: {bundleEncrypted, bundleIv, shareSalt, scopeType, note}
	•	If singleUse=true, token is immediately revoked at this point
	•	UI shows: share details + passphrase entry form
	•	Recipient enters passphrase → browser runs PBKDF2(passphrase, shareSalt) → shareKey
	•	Browser decrypts bundle with shareKey → displays KEY=VALUE pairs with copy/download options
What the recipient sees if they get the passphrase wrong
AES-GCM authentication tag verification fails — decryption throws an error
UI shows: 'Incorrect passphrase. Please try again.'
No indication of how many attempts remain (no brute-force hint surface)
After 5 failed attempts: 30-second cooldown enforced client-side

10. UI/UX Specification
10.1 Screen Map
Screen
Key Interactions
/login
Email + password or magic link. Redirects to /dashboard if session active.
/register
Name + email + password. Sends verification email.
/dashboard
Project grid. New project button. Vault lock indicator in navbar.
Vault Unlock (modal)
Master password input. Shown over any vault page when key not in memory. Handles PBKDF2 derive.
/projects/[id]
Environment tabs (dev, staging, prod). Quick stats per environment.
/projects/[id]/[envId]
Three-pane layout: sidebar folder tree + main secrets table + detail panel.
/projects/[id]/[envId]/[folderId]
Same three-pane. Breadcrumb updates. Secrets scoped to this folder.
/share/[token]
Public page. Share summary + passphrase form + decrypted values table. No auth required.
/settings
Master password change, auto-lock timeout, 2FA setup, active shares management, account delete.
10.2 Vault Unlock Modal
This is the critical security step between account login and vault access. It appears automatically when:
	•	User navigates to any vault page and the derived key is not in memory
	•	Auto-lock timer has expired
	•	User manually clicks the lock icon
	•	Page is refreshed or reopened
The modal is full-screen overlay, non-dismissible (ESC does nothing), with a single master password input. After correct entry, PBKDF2 runs in the browser (~1-2 seconds due to 600k iterations — intentional). A progress indicator shows during derivation. Wrong password shows a generic error, no retry limit shown.
10.3 Secrets Table (Main Vault View)
Each row in the secrets table shows:
	•	KEY_NAME — always visible (stored plaintext in DB as metadata)
	•	Value — shown as ••••••••••••• until the eye icon is clicked
	•	Reveal: decrypts in browser, shows value for 30 seconds then re-masks
	•	Copy: decrypts, copies to clipboard, clears clipboard after 30 seconds, shows countdown
	•	Edit: opens inline edit with the decrypted value pre-filled
	•	History: dropdown of last 5 values with timestamps, each individually decryptable
	•	Tags: colored chips, clickable to filter
	•	Delete: confirm dialog, then hard delete (secret + all history)

11. Environment Variables
Create a .env.local file at the project root. Never commit this file.
# Database (Neon serverless Postgres recommended for Vercel)
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://user:pass@host/envault?sslmode=require"
 
# NextAuth
NEXTAUTH_URL="http://localhost:3000"          # change to prod URL on deploy
NEXTAUTH_SECRET="your-random-32-char-secret"  # openssl rand -base64 32
 
# Resend (email service)
RESEND_API_KEY="re_xxxxxxxxxxxx"
RESEND_FROM="EnVault <noreply@yourdomain.com>"
 
# Upstash Redis (rate limiting)
UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_URL="https://xxx.upstash.io"
UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_TOKEN="your-token"
 
# App
NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL="http://localhost:3000"
SHARE_LINK_BASE="http://localhost:3000/share"

12. Deployment Guide (Vercel)
	•	Create a Neon (neon.tech) or Supabase PostgreSQL database — copy the connection string
	•	Create an Upstash Redis database (upstash.com) — copy REST URL and token
	•	Create a Resend account (resend.com), verify your domain, get API key
	•	Push code to GitHub repository
	•	Import repo to Vercel, add all environment variables from section 11
	•	Run database migrations: vercel env pull .env.local && npx prisma migrate deploy
	•	Deploy. Vercel auto-deploys on every push to main.

13. Implementation Phases
Phase 1 — Foundation (Week 1)
	•	Project setup: Next.js 14, TypeScript, Tailwind, shadcn/ui, Prisma
	•	Database schema creation and first migration
	•	NextAuth setup with email/password (credentials provider)
	•	Vault unlock flow: PBKDF2 derivation, Zustand store, auto-lock
	•	Middleware: session protection, route guards
Phase 2 — Core Vault (Week 2)
	•	Project CRUD UI and API routes
	•	Environment management
	•	Folder tree: creation, nesting, navigation
	•	Secret CRUD: add/edit/delete/reveal with full AES-256-GCM encrypt/decrypt
	•	Copy to clipboard with 30-second clear
Phase 3 — Files + Import/Export (Week 3)
	•	VaultFile: creation, editor, download
	•	Bulk import (.env paste parser)
	•	Export .env and .zip of project
	•	Secret history (versioning)
Phase 4 — Sharing System (Week 4)
	•	Share creation modal: scope selection, passphrase, expiry options
	•	Share bundle encryption (re-encrypt with share key)
	•	Resend email integration: share link email template
	•	Public share page: token validation, passphrase entry, decrypted view
	•	Share management: active shares list, revoke, audit log
Phase 5 — Polish + Security Hardening (Week 5)
	•	CSP headers, CORS settings, HSTS
	•	Rate limiting on auth + share endpoints via Upstash
	•	Master password change (re-encrypt all secrets)
	•	2FA (TOTP) setup and verification
	•	Search across key names
	•	Mobile-responsive UI
	•	Full security audit against the threat model

14. Pre-Launch Security Checklist
Cryptography
	•	All encryption uses AES-256-GCM with a fresh 12-byte random IV per operation
	•	PBKDF2 uses minimum 600,000 iterations with SHA-256
	•	PBKDF2 salt is 32 bytes of cryptographically random data
	•	CryptoKey is not extractable (extractable: false in importKey call)
	•	AAD (Additional Authenticated Data) is set to bind ciphertext to its context
	•	Master password is never sent to the server in any form
	•	Derived key is cleared from memory on lock/logout/page unload
	•	Share passphrase is never sent to the server
API & Server
	•	All vault API routes verify session via getServerSession before any DB access
	•	DB queries always filter by userId to prevent horizontal privilege escalation
	•	Share token lookup validates expiry, revocation, and single-use status atomically
	•	Rate limiting applied to: /api/auth/*, /api/share/*, /api/vault/salt
	•	Zod validation on all API inputs — no raw request body access
	•	Error responses never leak stack traces or DB query details in production
Headers & Transport
	•	HTTPS enforced via Vercel (automatic) + HSTS header set
	•	Content-Security-Policy header set: no unsafe-inline, no eval
	•	X-Frame-Options: DENY to prevent clickjacking
	•	X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
	•	Referrer-Policy: no-referrer
	•	Cookies: HttpOnly, Secure, SameSite=Strict
Application
	•	VaultUnlock modal is non-dismissible — no way to bypass it
	•	Auto-lock fires on inactivity and page visibility change (visibilitychange event)
	•	Clipboard auto-clear runs even if the component unmounts before the 30s timer
	•	No secret values are ever logged to console or error reporting services
	•	Import parser handles malformed .env files gracefully without executing content
	•	Share recipient page shows no error detail on invalid token (generic 404)

Quick Start
# Clone and install
git clone https://github.com/you/envault.git
cd envault
npm install
 
# Set up environment
cp .env.example .env.local
# Edit .env.local with your database URL, NextAuth secret, Resend API key
 
# Set up database
npx prisma migrate dev --name init
npx prisma generate
 
# Run development server
npm run dev
# Open http://localhost:3000

EnVault
Built with security as the only compromise-free requirement.
